# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-case-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-case-baseball/100-yard-dash] The **100-yard dash** is a track and field sprint event of 100 yards (91.44 metres).
[src:george-case-baseball/100-yard-dash] It was part of the Commonwealth Games until 1970, and was included in the triathlon of the Olympics in 1904.
[src:george-case-baseball/100-yard-dash] It is not generally used in international events, replaced by the 100-metre sprint (109.36 yards).
[src:george-case-baseball/100-yard-dash] However, it is still occasionally run in the United States in certain competitions; in the NCAA championships it was last run in 1975.
[src:george-case-baseball/100-yard-dash] Walter Halben Butler (1852–1931) is credited with being the first to run the race in 10 seconds.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1937 throughout the world.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per Seamheads.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of either established leagues.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The **1937 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1937.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 34th World Series on October 6 and ended with Game 5 on October 10.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] In the fifth iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Giants, four games to one, capturing their sixth championship in franchise history, and their second in a four-World Series run.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] With this victory, the Yankees became the team with the most World Series victories, a feat that continues today.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The fifth All-Star Game was held on July 7 at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., home of the Washington Senators.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The 1937 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 19, featured four teams across both leagues play.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 3 and featured all sixteen teams, the first since 1935.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 6 and October 10.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] 13 tie games (9 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 6 and ended on October 10 with the New York Yankees defeating the New York Giants in the 1937 World Series in five games.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] Over 78 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 63 games at League Park and 15 games at Cleveland Stadium.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] Only Sunday and Monday home games saw games played at Cleveland Stadium.
[src:george-case-baseball/1937-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 3rd of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:george-case-baseball/1939-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1939 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the seventh playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:george-case-baseball/1939-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 11, 1939, at Yankee Stadium in The Bronx, New York City, the home of the New York Yankees of the American League.
[src:george-case-baseball/1939-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the American League defeating the National League 3–1.
[src:george-case-baseball/1939-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The Yankees went on the win the World Series that year, making them the first team to host the All-Star Game and win the World Series in the same year.
[src:george-case-baseball/1939-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:george-case-baseball/1939-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Hubbard and Magerkurth swapped positions, also Goetz and Rommel swapped positions.
[src:george-case-baseball/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1940 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the eighth playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:george-case-baseball/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 9, 1940, at Sportsman's Park in St.
[src:george-case-baseball/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis, Missouri, the home of both the St.
[src:george-case-baseball/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals of the National League (who were the designated host team) and the St.
[src:george-case-baseball/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the National League defeating the American League 4–0.
[src:george-case-baseball/1940-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Reardon and Basil swapped positions, also Pipgras and Stewart swapped positions.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1943 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 11th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 13, 1943, at Shibe Park in Philadelphia, the home of the Philadelphia Athletics of the American League.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the American League defeating the National League 5–3.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first major league All-Star Game scheduled as a night game.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Left fielder Dick Wakefield became only the second rookie player in MLB history to start in an All-Star Game after Joe DiMaggio, (1939).
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The lone representative of the host team was Dick Siebert, starting first baseman for the AL, who was hitless in one at bat.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Rommel and Dunn swapped positions, also Conlan and Rue swapped positions.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL started the game with two singles, then scored one run on a sacrifice fly by Stan Musial.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL jumped ahead 3–1 in the bottom of the 2nd, on a pair of walks followed by a home run from Bobby Doerr.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL added a run in the 3rd, on back-to-back doubles by Ken Keltner and Dick Wakefield, and another run in the bottom of the 5th, on an error by NL second baseman Billy Herman with runners on first and third with two outs; the AL was up 5–1.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL later got two runs back from Vince DiMaggio; in the 7th he hit a triple and then scored on a sacrifice fly by Dixie Walker, and in the 9th he led off the inning with a home run.
[src:george-case-baseball/1943-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] But the NL was unable to rally further, resulting in an AL 5–3 victory.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1945 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was cancelled on April 24 after the Major League Baseball (MLB) season began on April 17.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The July 10 game was cancelled due to wartime travel restrictions in World War II.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] 1945 is the first of two years since 1933, when the first official All-Star Game was played, that an All-Star Game was cancelled and All-Stars were not officially selected.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was to have been the 13th annual playing of the "Midsummer Classic" by MLB's American League (AL) and National League (NL) All-Star teams.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was to be played at Fenway Park, home of the AL's Boston Red Sox.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Fenway Park was chosen for the 1946 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (13th "Midsummer Classic") which was played on July 9 of that year.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] On July 9 and 10, 1945, seven out of eight scheduled interleague night games were advertised and played as "All-Star" games in place of the official All-Star Game during the three-day All-Star break to help support the American Red Cross and the National War Fund.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Four of the exhibition games were played on July 10 in Washington, D.C., St.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Mike Todd, a Broadway producer, had passed on the idea of holding the 1945 All-Star Game in Nuremberg, at a stadium renamed "Soldier Field" where U.S. troops stationed in the European Theater played baseball.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Although baseball's new commissioner, Happy Chandler was reportedly "intrigued" by the idea, it was ultimately dismissed as impractical by military advisors.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The next time an All-Star game got cancelled was the 2020 game due to the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] No MLB players were officially named to the All-Star teams in 1945, due to the cancellation of the All-Star Game.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The All-Star rosters for the AL and NL All-Star teams were to have been selected by each All-Star squad's manager (from 1935 through 1946), which did not occur that season.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Sporting News* (TSN) named an annual major league All-Star Team from 1925 to 1961 (from 1961 to present an American and National League team is named) from a Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWA) members ballot.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A group of sportswriters of the Associated Press (AP) did name 40 AL and NL All-Stars in 1945, after taking nominations from 13 of the 16 MLB managers that season.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The managers who did not participate were Joe McCarthy of the New York Yankees, Luke Sewell of the St.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Browns, and Billy Southworth of the St.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Sewell (AL) and Southworth (NL) were the 1944 pennant championship team's managers and were to have managed the 1945 All-Star Game teams.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Although Sewell could not officially select anyone for the AL All-Star roster, he listed his personal AL All-Stars as pitcher Dave Ferriss of the Red Sox and third baseman Tony Cuccinello of the White Sox.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Fred Lieb a sportswriter for the *Sporting News* (TSN) also wrote an article in the July 12, 1945, issue selecting 40 All-stars for the two All-Star teams, even naming starting position players and three possible starting pitchers.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Some of Lieb's selections are different than the AP selections.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The annual TSN All-Stars list is released after the season.
[src:george-case-baseball/1945-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Tigers catcher, Paul Richards is the only annual TSN All-Star not in the AP and Lieb selections for 1945.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] As of his retirement as a player in 1947, Case ranked ninth in American League history and third in Senators history with 349 career stolen bases, and he had the most stolen bases of any player between 1930 and 1960.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] As of 2026, he is the only player in history to lead both major leagues in stolen bases for five consecutive seasons and tied Ty Cobb with six American League stolen base titles, a record later broken by Luis Aparicio.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] George Washington Case Jr. was born on November 11, 1915 in Trenton, New Jersey to George and Clara (née McIntyre) Case.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] George Sr. was a butcher and successful businessman who had popularized pork roll through his store Case's, which he founded in 1874.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He had also been a noted sprinter as a young man.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] George Jr. had two sisters, Audrey and Gladys, and one half-brother from his father's previous marriage, W.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His half-brother was a former professional baseball player who had retired to run Case's, and he encouraged young George Jr. to play baseball and basketball.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] After attending Gregory Elementary School and Junior High Three in Trenton, Case graduated from Trenton Central High School in 1934, where he was first-team all-New Jersey in both baseball and basketball.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He earned the nicknamed "Casey" after his penchant for reciting *Casey at the Bat* to teammates and relatives and played in a 1934 exhibition game with Philadelphia Athletics star Jimmie Foxx, who became a personal friend and would visit the Case family in Trenton.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] After graduating from Trenton High, Case weighed whether to accept a scholarship to Brown University or go professional; he attended the Peddie School from 1934 to 1936 while continuing to try out for major league teams.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case was first scouted by Athletics owner-manager Connie Mack, who advised Case to switch from second baseman to outfielder, where he remained for his entire career.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] However, the Athletics did not need another outfielder, and Mack recommended Case to Washington Senators owner Clark Griffith.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He was signed by Washington scout Joe Cambria in 1936.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case joined the York White Roses of the New York–Penn League, but the team was quickly purchased by his half-brother Cliff and relocated to Trenton as the Trenton Senators.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] During two seasons in the minor leagues, Case batted .313 in 175 games.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case made his major league debut with the Senators in September 1937.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] After failing to get a hit in his first two games, Case finished the season strong, batting .289 in 93 at-bats.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In 1938, his first full season, Case hit .305 in 107 games.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His breakout season came in 1939, when Case hit .302 and led the Senators in runs scored (103) and the entire American League in steals (51).
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He was selected for an All-Star Game for the first time and named New Jersey Professional Athlete of the Year.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case would dominate the American League stolen bases leaderboard for the next eight years, winning six stolen base titles.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] On April 30, 1939, Case caught the final ball hit by Lou Gehrig before his retirement due to ALS, and he was on the field during Gehrig's farewell address at Yankee Stadium.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case continued to blossom into a star in the early 1940s and was widely considered the fastest man in the baseball.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Clyde Milan, who set the Senators record for stolen bases, said, "George Case was the fastest man ever to play baseball. ...
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He was faster than Ty Cobb, Eddie Collins, [and] Max Carey." In 1943, Case was clocked rounding the bases from a standing start in 13.5 seconds, breaking a record set by Hans Lobert.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He led both major leagues in stolen bases for five consecutive seasons from 1939 to 1943, a record which still stands as of 2026, and his 61 stolen bases in 1943 were the most of any player in the first four decades of the live-ball era, from 1921 until 1961.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case's speed also made him very difficult to turn a double play against; as of 2013, Case's rate of one double play per 94 at-bats ranked among the top five in baseball history.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In addition to his raw speed, Case was also known for his judicious baserunning.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] "Baseball was played a lot differently then," he said.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] "I never stole third with two out or stole second when we were three or four runs down.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In the 1940s, there were right and wrong times to run." Case was also expected to decide when to run on his own, with a signal from the third base coach, and claimed that he was never given a sign by Bucky Harris or Ossie Bluege during his time in Washington.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In addition to his remarkable baserunning, Case continued to develop at the plate and in the field, setting career highs in hits in 1940, leading the American League in outfield assists in 1941, and batting a career-high .320 in 1942.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] However, Case suffered badly from back and shoulder injuries, and his career rapidly declined in 1944 and 1945.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His batting average and run production fell off, and he was beaten by New York Yankees star Snuffy Stirnweiss for the stolen base title in each season.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In December 1945, Case was traded to the Cleveland Indians for veteran outfielder Jeff Heath.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Although Indians manager Lou Boudreau remarked that he was relieved that he would no longer have to worry about "that pest" on the bases, Case took a much more conservative approach to baserunning and finished the season with only 28 stolen bases.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] However, this was enough to secure him his sixth and final stolen base title, tying Ty Cobb for the American League record.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] During Case's only season in Cleveland, Indians owner Bill Veeck staged a promotion matching Case against Jesse Owens in a 100-yard race.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In another promotional race against Senators rookie Gil Coan, Case ran a 100-yard dash in ten seconds flat, despite suffering from a bad back.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In March 1947, Case was traded back to the Senators for Roger Wolff.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] After hitting .150 average in 36 games, he played his final major league game on August 3, 1947 and announced his retirement at the age of 31.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His 321 stolen bases ranked third in Senators history and ninth in American League history.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Immediately after retiring from baseball, Case opened George Case's Sports Center, a sporting goods store in Trenton, and ran it until 1960.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In 1950, Case was hired to coach the Rutgers University baseball team.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] "I've missed baseball a lot since retiring," he told the *Central New Jersey Home News*.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] During his first year as a coach, the team finished the regular season 17-4-1 and qualified for the College World Series.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In their opening game, they rallied to defeat Texas, the defending national champions, 4-2.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] However, in the winners' bracket final, Rutgers lost in extra innings to Washington State and ultimately finished third after losing to Texas, who repeated as champions.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] As of 2020, this was the only College World Series appearance in Rutgers history.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Over his ten years as head coach, Rutgers compiled a record of 116 wins, 84 losses, and 3 draws, making Case the winningest coach in Rutgers history.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His records for wins and winning percentage were later surpassed by Fred Hill.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case's son, George III, played for Rutgers during his final season as head coach.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He also hosted a daily radio show on WTTM from 1958 to 1960.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In 1961, Case accepted an opportunity to return to the major leagues as the third base coach for the new expansion Senators under his former teammate and friend, Mickey Vernon.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He remained with the Seantors from 1961 until 1963.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] From 1965 until 1966, he managed the Hawaii Islanders in the Pacific Coast League.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His final major league job was with the Minnesota Twins in 1968.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He managed the Oneonta Yankees from 1969 to 1972, winning Manager of the Year twice, and was a scout for the Yankees, Texas Rangers, and Seattle Mariners from 1974 to 1979.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] His final job in baseball was as a minor league batting instructor for the Seattle Mariners from 1980 until 1985, when illness forced him to retire, ending a nearly five-decade career in baseball.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case married his neighbor and childhood sweetheart, Helen Farrell, in 1937.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] They had two children: George III, who was executive director of the Society for American Baseball Research from 2000 to 2002, and Robin Davis.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Case was a lifelong duck hunter and during his retirement served as a guide for hunters in Barnegat Bay.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] One of his grandsons played professional hockey for the Pittsburgh Penguins organization and in Sweden.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] Near the end of his life, Case lived in Morrisville, Bucks County, Pennsylvania.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He died of emphysema on January 23, 1989 in Trenton.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He was buried at the First Presbyterian Church Cemetery of Ewing.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] In addition to his major league records, Case was inducted into the Peddie School Athletic Hall of Fame, where was named Athlete of the Century, and the New Jersey Sportswriters Hall of Fame.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] He was posthumously inducted into the Washington Hall of Stars, the Trenton Thunder Hall of Fame, and the New Jersey Interscholastic Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:george-case-baseball/george-case-baseball] After his death, George III compiled interviews and clips from his father's life and career into a short documentary film, *Around the League: 1939–1946*, which is dedicated to the memory of the late George Case Jr.
